{
  "text": "Few data on surface water contamination by medicines and hormones via land are found in literature. A selection is briefly discussed below to add further considerations to the validity of screening level surface water exposure models. Ivermectin has a sorption coefficient K om of 4500-5500 l kg \u22121 and is rather persistent in soil with degradation half-lives DT50 (determined at 22 \u00b0C under laboratory conditions) of 93 to 240 days (mean 187 days, n = 4) [CITATION_1] . Transport of ivermectin by drainage is to be considered negligible, since this route is not assessed in the EMEA model at Koc > 500 l kg \u22121",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "85434948"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "85434948": {
      "title": "The environmental impact of the use of ivermectin: environmental effects and fate",
      "abstract": "Abstract The environmental effects and fate of ivermectin were studied either as the pure compound or in feces. Toxicities to microbes, earthworms, algae, fish, and Daphnia, soil-binding parameters and degradation half-lives were determined."
    }
  }
}